{"url": "https://www.ejcancer.com/article/S0959-8049(18)30035-2/fulltext", "title": "Cancer cells regulate Interleukin-22 production to promote tumor growth", "author": "C. Voigt", "affli": "Division of Clinical Pharmacology, Department of Medicine IV, University Hospital, Ludwig Maximilian University of Munich, Munich, Germany", "session": "P02.03", "doi": "DOI: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ejca.2018.01.021", "text": "\nBackground:\nInterleukin-22 (IL-22) has been identified as a major driver of tumor development and progression in various tumor entities including breast, lung or colon cancer. There, IL-22 has been ascribed as arising from different immune cells such as T cells, innate lymphoid cells or myeloid cells. However, little evidence so far exists that would provide a link between the widely described function of IL-22 and its regulation in cancer tissue.", "keywords": ""}
