{"url": "https://www.ejcancer.com/article/S0959-8049(18)30059-5/fulltext", "title": "HAGE-derived peptide as a vaccine to prevent relapse in TNBC patients: Proof of concepts", "author": "D. Nagarajan", "affli": "NTU, Nottingham, United Kingdom", "session": "P06.02", "doi": "DOI: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ejca.2018.01.045", "text": "\nBackground:\nTriple Negative Breast Cancers (TNBC) account for 15% of all breast cancer and are one of the most aggressive type and have poor long-term prognosis. Moreover, there are currently no approved targeted therapies and chemotherapy remains the mainstay of treatment for early and advanced disease. The level of immune infiltrate in TNBC has been linked to a more favourable outcome and lower mutation and neoantigen counts, indicating that an active immune surveillance is ongoing and that these patients might benefit form a combination of checkpoint inhibitor therapy and antigen specific vaccination.", "keywords": ""}
