{"url": "https://www.ejcancer.com/article/S0959-8049(18)30071-6/fulltext", "title": "Enhancing Cytokine-Induced Killer (CIK) cell activity with Her2-specific Fc-engineered antibodies and antibody derivatives", "author": "E. Cappuzzello", "affli": "Department of Surgery, Oncology and Gastroenterology, Immunology and Oncology Section, University of Padua, Padua, Italy", "session": "P09.02", "doi": "DOI: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ejca.2018.01.057", "text": "\nBackground:\nCytokine-Induced Killer (CIK) cells are a heterogeneous population of ex vivo expanded lymphocytes which exhibit an MHC-unrestricted cytotoxicity against a wide range of tumor histotypes. Moreover, recent reports have also proven that CIK cells express CD16 in a donor-dependent manner, which makes them able to exert Antibody Dependent Cell-Mediated Cytotoxicity (ADCC)[1]. In this study, we aimed at increasing CIK cell antitumor activity using Fc-engineered trastuzumab, bispecific antibodies or recombinant immunoligands, which are able to target both a tumor-associated antigen (Her2) and activating receptors expressed by CIK cells (CD3, NKG2D and NKp30).", "keywords": ""}
